II. ERROR CHECK

To check the potential discrepancy in the database, Ive made the checking_error_pedigree() function which test different criteria / source of error which are tested :

  1. IDs are all present in the dataset i.e.if missing IDs from the whole population of the study population

  2. The presence of non unique id in individual_id

  3. Presence of an emergence date OR a capture date

  4. Mismatch between emergence date and first capture date

  5. Social parent in individual_id modalities

  6. Presence of sex

  7. Mismatch parents sexe e.g.if a mother is a female

# ERROR CHECK
#' @param all_id : complete list of individual ID e.g. reference list (default = NULL)
#' @param individual_id : dataset individual unique IDs vector
#' @param mother_id : mother IDs vector 
#' @param father_id : father IDs vector 
#' @param emergence_date : emergence dates vector (default = NULL)
#' @param capture_date : capture dates vector (default = NULL)
#' @param sexe : individual's sex vector (default = NULL)

error <- checking_error_pedigree(all_id = total_individual_id$individual_id,
                                individual_id = pedigree_actu$individual_id,
                                mother_id = pedigree_actu$mere_soc,
                                father_id = pedigree_actu$pere_soc,
                                emergence_date = pedigree_actu$date_emergence,
                                capture_date = pedigree_actu$date_capture,
                                sexe = pedigree_actu$sexe
                                )
## No problem detected in the pedigree.

Missing parent as dummy variables

We replace the missing parent by a dummy variable for each parent. A FILTRER PAR ANNEE.

# One missing parent == NA as dummy_variable parent
row_missing_parent <- which(xor(is.na(pedigree_data$mother), is.na(pedigree_data$father)))
missing_parent <- pedigree_data[row_missing_parent,]
id_single_mother <- names(table(missing_parent$mother))  # mother's id from missing father family
id_single_father <- names(table(missing_parent$father))  # father's id from missing mother family

 # Replace 'NA' of missing father for each family by a dummy father D[i]
for(i in 1:length(id_single_mother)){
  rows_missing_father <- which(pedigree_data$mother == id_single_mother[i] & is.na(pedigree_data$father))
  pedigree_data[rows_missing_father, "father"] <- paste0("Df",i)
  # adding dummy parent as dummy individual in individual ID column
  pedigree_data[rows_missing_father, "father"] <- paste0("Df",i)
  pedigree_data[nrow(pedigree_data)+1, c("individual_id", "sexe")] <- c(paste0("Df",i), "m")
}

# Replace 'NA' of missing mother for each family by a dummy mother D[i]
for(i in 1:length(id_single_father)){
  rows_missing_mother <- which(pedigree_data$father == id_single_father[i] & is.na(pedigree_data$mother))
  pedigree_data[rows_missing_mother, "mother"] <- paste0("Dm",i)
  # adding dummy parent as dummy individual in individual ID column
  pedigree_data[rows_missing_mother, "mother"] <- paste0("Dm",i)
  pedigree_data[nrow(pedigree_data)+1, c("individual_id", "sexe")] <- c(paste0("Dm",i), "f")
}


Ordering pedigree

Offsprings must follow parents. This step is needed for the function of the kinship2 package to work properly (and for animal model).

# SOCIAL
pedigree_data <- pedigree_data[nrow(pedigree_data):1,]
ord <- pedigree::orderPed(pedigree_data)  
pedigree_data <- pedigree_data[order(ord),]

#GENETIC
pedigree_data_gen <- pedigree_data_gen[nrow(pedigree_data_gen):1,]
ord <- pedigree::orderPed(pedigree_data_gen)  
pedigree_data_gen <- pedigree_data_gen[order(ord),]

Pedigree pruning

Pruning a pedigree means removing non-informative individuals (e.g.individual with no phenotype data or individuals from which we could not infer any genetic parameters).

# ONLY CONSIDER DATA USABLE FOR ANIMAL MODEL (NO NAs)
pheno_complete <- pheno[!is.na(pheno$annee_emergence) & 
                      !is.na(pheno$age_emergence) &
                      !is.na(pheno$litter_size_naissance) &
                      !is.na(pheno$territoire) &
                      !is.na(pheno$taille_groupe_naissance),]
#' [PRUNING]
 for(response_variable in c("masse", "tibia", "cubitus", "zygo", "longueur_corps", "mandibule")){
    # No NAs response variable
    informative_id <- pheno_complete[which(!is.na(pheno_complete[response_variable])), 'individual_id']
    
    # Pruning pedigree according to available data
    pruned_pedigree <- prunePed(pedigree = pedigree_data[1:3],
            keep = informative_id,  # IDs of informative individual (i.e. with measures)
            make.base = T)
    
    # Number of individual pruned
    amplitude_prune <-  nrow(pedigree_data) - nrow(pruned_pedigree)
    
    print(
      paste0(toupper(x = response_variable), " : NUMBER OF PRUNED INDIVIDUAL = ", amplitude_prune)
      )
 }

II. GENERATION OF THE SOCIAL VARIABLES

Note that here, social variables generation code are not evaluated. The effective code that generate them is in PHENOTYPE.R

Sex ratio of the subordinates

Sex ratio is calculated as : \(\frac{male - 1}{(male-1) + (female-1)}\). The -1 aims to remove the dominant couple to only consider subordinates. Only adults and 2 years old individuals were included in this calcul.

pheno["sex_ratio_subordinates"] <-
  apply(pheno, 1, function(x) {
    male_sub <-
      ifelse((as.numeric(x["compo_m_2"]) + as.numeric(x["compo_m_ad"]) - 1) <= 0,
             0, (as.numeric(x["compo_m_2"]) + as.numeric(x["compo_m_ad"]) - 1))
    female_sub <-
      ifelse((as.numeric(x["compo_f_2"]) + as.numeric(x["compo_f_ad"]) - 1) <= 0,
             0, (as.numeric(x["compo_f_2"]) + as.numeric(x["compo_f_ad"]) - 1))
    
    return(ifelse(male_sub == 0 & female_sub == 0, NA, male_sub / (male_sub + female_sub)
    ))
  })

pheno["nb_male_subordinates"] <- (pheno$compo_m_2 + pheno$compo_m_ad - 1)

Litter size / group size / composition of the group at birth

we selection the state of social variables (sex ratio of subordinates, group size) at the emergence date of the individual to characterize the social status of the group at birth for each individual.

# SELECT SOCIAL VARIABLES AT THE EMERGENCE DATE
ref_birth <-
  pheno %>%
  filter(annee_emergence == annee_territoire) %>%  # select the social group state at emergence's year
  dplyr::select(
    c(
      individual_id,
      taille_groupe,
      litter_size,
      sex_ratio_subordinates,
      nb_male_subordinates,
      presence_male_subordinates
    )
  ) %>%  # /!\ select enters in conflict with MASS::select() if not specified dplyr::
  distinct(individual_id, .keep_all = T)  # filtering repeated observations to only take one (to remove individual recaptured the same year of their emergence)



# RENAMING NEW VARIABLES
names(ref_birth)[2:ncol(ref_birth)] <-
  c(
    "taille_groupe_naissance",
    "litter_size_naissance",
    "sex_ratio_subordinates_naissance",
    "nb_male_subordinates_naissance",
    "presence_male_subordinates_naissance"
  )

# MERGING WITH DATASET
pheno <- merge(x = pheno, y = ref_birth, by = "individual_id", all = T, all.y = T, sort = F)







III. ERROR CHECK

The function checking_error_data() checks for :

  • The uniqueness of capture IDs

  • The presence of all individual IDs from the dataset in the pedigree

  • The presence of all individual IDs from the pedigree in the dataset

  • Mismatch between the year of capture and the year of territory observation

  • Presence of measures at emergence while litter size == 0

  • Group size is not equal to the sum of adults + young (1 year) + yearling

  • Group size == NA while group composition is available

  • Presence of some NAs (not all) in group composition

#' @param capture_id : a vector containing all the capture IDs 
#' @param pedigree_individual_id : a vector containing all the individual IDs of the pedigree
#' @param data_individual_id : a vector containing all the individual IDs of the dataset 
#' @param capture_year : a vector containing the capture's years 
#' @param territoire_year : a vector containing the observation's territory years
#' @param litter_size_at_birth : a vector containing the litter size at birth
#' @param df_group_composition : a data_frame containing the group size in first column and one year adults and yearlings for the other

error_data <- checking_error_data(
  capture_id = pheno$capture_id,
  pedigree_individual_id = pedigree_data$individual_id,
  data_individual_id = pheno$individual_id,
  capture_year = pheno$annee_capture,
  territoire_year = pheno$annee_territoire,
  litter_size_at_birth = pheno$litter_size_naissance,
  df_group_composition = pheno[c(which(names(pheno) == "taille_groupe"),
                                 # select all but pups
                                 which(names(pheno) %in% grep(pattern = "compo", x = names(pheno), value = T) & 
                                         !(names(pheno) %in% grep(pattern = "0", x = names(pheno), value = T))))]
  )
## 
## ====================================================================== 
## ========================== PROBLEM DETECTED ==========================
## ======================================================================

IDENTIFIABILITY OF PARAMETERS

The idea here is to determine how many phenotype observations x non-NAs predictor available for each effect to calculate.

First, we filter the dataset with only non-NAs predictor values. As the response variable weight and size have almost no NAs, I decided to ignore it for visualization purpose and readability (i.e.to avoid representing each time results for wieght AND size).

pheno_complete <- pheno[!is.na(pheno$annee_emergence) & 
                      !is.na(pheno$age_emergence) &
                      !is.na(pheno$litter_size_naissance) &
                      !is.na(pheno$territoire) &
                      !is.na(pheno$taille_groupe_naissance),]

I. Random effects

Maternal effects

For the maternal effects, we need to consider :

  • The number of repetition per mother
  • The number of different partner theyve had (number of half sibs)

Number of phenotype data with repeated mother

# EXTRACT ID OF MOTHER WITH REPEATED MEASURES (>2)
mother_table <- table(pedigree_data$mother)
mother_repeated <- mother_table[mother_table > 1]
id_mother_repeated <- names(mother_repeated)
paste0("NUMBER OF MOTHER WITH MORE THAN 1 OFFSPRING : ", length(id_mother_repeated), " (", round(length(id_mother_repeated) / length(unique(pedigree_data$mother)), 2)*100, "%)")
## [1] "NUMBER OF MOTHER WITH MORE THAN 1 OFFSPRING : 158 (96%)"


Now were determining the number of phenotype observation available for each mother with more than 1 offspring.

rep_per_mother <- 
  pheno_complete[pheno_complete$individual_id %in% id_mother_repeated, ] %>% 
  group_by(individual_id) %>% 
  summarise(n = n())

Number of phenotype data with mother with different partner

Now were determining the number of phenotype observation available for each mother with more than 2 partners. This information will help quantify the additive genetic maternal effect as it will allow the decomposition of maternal versus common environmental effect among members of a litter.

# NUMBER OF UNIQUE PARTNER PER MOTHER
partner_per_mother <- 
  pedigree_data %>% 
  group_by(mother) %>% 
  summarise(n = n_distinct(father)) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# EXTRACT ID OF MOTHER WITH SEVERAL PARTNERS
id_mother_partner_repeated <- partner_per_mother$mother[partner_per_mother$n > 1]

OBSERVER BIAS

Observers have only been reported since 2013. We first check if theres any observer effect during this period.


Testing for presence of bias in size

# NUMBER OF MEASURES PER OBSERVERS
observer_sample <- pheno_complete[pheno_complete$annee_capture %in% 13:23 & !is.na(pheno_complete$tibia),] %>% 
  group_by(operateur_id) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))

observer_sample




To check observer bias, we will only select the operator that have measured more than 200 individuals, the other will be NAs.

# EXTRACT MAIN OBSERVER
main_observer <- unlist(observer_sample[observer_sample$n > 200, "operateur_id"])

# OTHER OBSERVER AS A DUMMY VARIABLE "NA"
pheno_complete[is.na(pheno_complete$operateur_id), "operateur_id"] <- "NA"  # NA as level of factor
pheno_complete$operateur_id <- as.factor(pheno_complete$operateur_id)
pheno_complete$operateur_id <- 
  pheno_complete$operateur_id %>% 
  fct_collapse("NA" = unlist(pheno_complete[!pheno_complete$operateur_id %in% main_observer, "operateur_id"]))

# FILTER DATAFRAME after 2013
data_main_observer <- pheno_complete[as.numeric(as.character(pheno_complete$annee_capture)) >=13,]



We evaluate the mean age of observation for each operator.

data_main_observer %>%
  group_by(operateur_id) %>%
  summarise(
    median_age = median(age_emergence),
    quantile_25 = quantile(age_emergence, probs = .25),
    quantile_75 = quantile(age_emergence, probs = .75),
    n = n()
  )


Here, the difficulty is to check if theres a structure of manipulation, for example, everything is good if operators measure individuals randomly, but if some operators tends to only measures the pups, it will be difficult to evaluate a potential observer effect. To test observer effect, well only consider the main operators and select individuals that have been measured several times by several operators. Well consider the response variable size for individuals with > 4 years old (i.e.with terminated growth).



Extract individuals measured per all observers and > 4 years old

repeated_measured_individual <- 
  data_main_observer[data_main_observer$operateur_id != "NA",] %>% 
  filter(age_emergence > 4*365) %>% 
  group_by(individual_id, operateur_id) %>%
  summarise(n = n())

repeated_individual_id <-  names(which(table(repeated_measured_individual$individual_id) > 1))



Plot size per operator
Note that we only plot the size of individuals >= 4 years old and measured by all operators. Each measure represent one individual which has attain its full growth. Therefore, the variance observed corresponds to the error of measure.

# DATA WITH AGE > 4
data_main_observer <- 
  data_main_observer %>% 
  filter(age_emergence > 365*4 & operateur_id %in% main_observer)

# MEASURED BY BOTH OBSERVER
data_main_observer <- data_main_observer[data_main_observer$individual_id %in% repeated_individual_id,]



Modelisation of partial residuals
We construct a constant model with individual ID as random effects. Then, we plot the residuals against the operator IDs to see which one tends to overestimate or underestimate the measure.

# REMOVING NAs
data_mod <- data_main_observer[!is.na(data_main_observer$tibia) &
                                 !is.na(data_main_observer$operateur_id),]

# CONSTANT MODEL
mod <- lme4::lmer(formula = log(tibia) ~ 1 + (1|individual_id), data = data_mod)
summary(mod)
